3 Accommodation challenges facing
Gypsies and Travellers
A shortage of suitable, secure accommodation contributes to many of the
inequalities that Gypsy and Traveller communities experience,20 and can be a
source of tension between travelling and settled communities.
3.1 Access to Traveller sites and housing
A shortage of suitable, authorised Traveller sites is often cited as a key reason
for Gypsy and Traveller households moving into conventional bricks-andmortar accommodation. However, some households may decide to give up a
mobile lifestyle (temporarily or permanently) for other reasons, for example
because of support needs relating to health or education.21
A 2022 research project on the lived experiences of Gypsy and Traveller
communities in England and Wales, commissioned by the Office for National
Statistics, found for some Gypsy and Travellers, living on the roadside was
seen as a necessity rather than a choice. Families described staying in laybys, car parks or transit sites (designed for temporary stays), sometimes for
several years at a time, because of an inability to access space on a
permanent Traveller site.22
An investigation by the charity Friends, Families and Travellers in 2021 (PDF)
identified that there were:
• only 59 available permanent pitches on local authority and registered
social provider Traveller sites in total in England, and
• at least 1,696 households on waiting lists for pitches on local authority
and registered social provider Traveller sites in England.23
