Although most Gypsies and Travellers now live in settled accommodation,
they can experience difficulties in accessing suitable housing and sustaining
tenancies. The charity Shelter’s good practice briefing on Gypsies and
Travellers provides an overview of some of these difficulties, including:
• discrimination
• distrust of public authorities
• low levels of literacy
• isolation from family support networks
• neighbourhood tensions24
In 2009, the Equality and Human Rights Commission published an evidence
review of the inequalities experienced by Gypsies and Travellers. This
identified that “ …although there is little published research into the
experiences of housed families and individuals, the wealth of anecdotal data
on experiences of racism, discrimination and poor health outcomes
associated with residence in housing, is compelling...25
Following an inquiry into the inequalities faced by Gypsy and Traveller
communities, the then Chair of the House of Commons Women and Equalities
Select Committee, Maria Miller, highlighted the committee’s concern that
although the majority of Gypsies and Travellers live in settled
accommodation, “Government policy making is overwhelmingly focused on
planning and encampments, and that these eclipse a wide range of other
important issues around policy and service provision.”26
