Under the homelessness legislation, a person applying to their local authority
for assistance will be deemed to be homeless if the accommodation available
for their occupation is a caravan and they do not have a place where they are
entitled, or permitted, to put it and live in it.
If a duty to secure accommodation arises in such cases, the local authority is
not required to make equivalent accommodation available (or provide a site
for the applicant’s own accommodation). However, the authority must
consider whether such options are reasonably available, particularly where
this would provide the most suitable solution to the applicant’s
accommodation needs.46
The statutory homelessness code of guidance for local authorities requires
authorities to consider the needs and lifestyle of applicants who are Gypsies
and Travellers when carrying out their homelessness duties:
…Where a duty to secure accommodation arises but an appropriate site is not
immediately available, the housing authority may need to provide an
alternative temporary solution until a suitable site, or some other suitable
option, becomes available. Some Gypsies and Travellers may have a cultural
aversion to the prospect of ‘bricks and mortar’ accommodation. In such cases,
the housing authority should seek to provide an alternative solution. However,
where the housing authority is satisfied that there is no prospect of a suitable
site for the time being, there may be no alternative solution. Housing
authorities must give consideration to the needs and lifestyle of applicants
who are Gypsies and Travellers when considering their application and how
best to discharge a duty to secure suitable accommodation, in line with their
obligations to act consistently with the Human Rights Act 1998, and in
particular the right to respect for private life, family and the home; as well as
their duties under section 149 of the Equality Act 2010.
